Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which underpins the euro by establishing constraints determining the size of the budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavyweight of the Union, has failed to meet its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Moreover, it has used its political weight to cover up the early warning of its deficit, issued by the European Commission in accordance with the terms of the Stability Pact.
Today it is France that is playing the bad boy.
The number 2 of the Union, somewhat unenthusiastic, has in turn unofficially declared its inability to meet its commitment to reduce its budget deficit, a year after the small Ireland received an official warning regarding its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the Stability Pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems greatly affected by the discussions aiming to eliminate it, as well as the discussions aiming to amend it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation is poorly done.
Limiting the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and ignores the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Admitting this fact, the architects of the pact worsened the situation by adopting two "poorly thought out" solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is practically impossible.
Concerned that serious slowdowns could undermine the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit was equivalent to zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a forecast budget for the next two years demonstrating how budgetary balance will be achieved in due time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable rate.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal policy of budgetary contraction.
The Commission, seeking to position itself as the guardian of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized that they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation of France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, notably regarding tax burden reduction.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it is not only a matter of political intelligence, but also economic intelligence, as long as budget expenditures are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges funded by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitely poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot meet its targets and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has become master at defying the laws of the Union.
Political maneuvers will inevitably follow.
Economists and cynics are not surprised at all.
The objective of the pact, to establish fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is entirely acceptable.
However, having lost control of their national monetary policy, Union members are left with only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The Stability Pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set by the bureaucrats in Brussels cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Luckily, we do not have to look far.
Monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy has been a real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it is enough to delegate this policy to a competent group, the central bank, granting it the necessary political independence, and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any deviation will have to be addressed in the future, it is up to them to exercise good sense.
This has proven to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Some, of course, fear losing democracy in the process.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive, and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of spending and in terms of revenues.
Decisions concerning these issues cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining budgetary balance to manage fluctuation cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain full control over its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term goal is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure its success, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must be the subject of a consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulations, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
